  "local_port": 49552,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which US Senate seats are up for reelection in 2018?",
  "response": "In the **2018 United States Senate elections**, a total of **35 seats** were contested. These included **33 regular elections** for Class I Senate seats and **2 special elections** to fill vacancies. Below is a comprehensive list of the states that held Senate elections in 2018, along with details about each race:\n\n### **Regular Elections (Class I):**\n\n1. **Alabama**\n   - **Seat:** Class II (open seat due to retirement of Senator Richard Shelby)\n   - **Result:** Tommy Tuberville (Republican) won the seat.\n\n2. **Alaska**\n   - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Mark Begich, Democrat)\n   - **Result:** Dan Sullivan (Republican) defeated Mark Begich.\n\n3. **Arizona**\n   - **Seat:** Class II (open seat due to retirement of Senator Jeff Flake)\n   - **Result:** Mark Kelly (Democrat) won the seat.\n\n4. **Arkansas**\n   - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent John Boozman, Republican)\n   - **Result:** John Boozman was re-elected.\n\n5. **Colorado**\n   - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Michael Bennet, Democrat)\n   - **Result:** Michael Bennet was re-elected.\n\n6. **Connecticut**\n   - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Chris Murphy, Democrat)\n   - **Result:** Chris Murphy was re-elected.\n\n7. **Delaware**\n   - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Tom Carper, Democrat)\n   - **Result:** Tom Carper was re-elected.\n\n8. **Florida**\n   - **Seat:** Class III (incumbent Rick Scott, Republican)\n   - **Result:** Rick Scott was re-elected.\n\n9. **Georgia**\n   - **Seat:** Class III (open seat due to retirement of Senator Johnny Isakson)\n   - **Result:** David Perdue (Republican) defeated Jon Ossoff (Democrat) in a runoff after no candidate received a majority in the general election.\n\n10. **Iowa**\n    - **Seat:** Class III (incumbent Chuck Grassley, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Chuck Grassley was re-elected.\n\n11. **Kansas**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Jerry Moran, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Jerry Moran was re-elected.\n\n12. **Kentucky**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Mitch McConnell, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Mitch McConnell was re-elected.\n\n13. **Louisiana**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent John Kennedy, Republican)\n    - **Result:** John Kennedy was re-elected.\n\n14. **Maine**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (independent Senator Angus King)\n    - **Result:** Angus King was re-elected.\n\n15. **Maryland**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Ben Cardin, Democrat)\n    - **Result:** Ben Cardin was re-elected.\n\n16. **Michigan**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Debbie Stabenow, Democrat)\n    - **Result:** Debbie Stabenow was re-elected.\n\n17. **Missouri**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Roy Blunt, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Josh Hawley (Republican) defeated Roy Blunt.\n\n18. **Montana**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Jon Tester, Democrat was not up; Steve Daines, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Steve Daines (Republican) won the seat.\n\n19. **Nebraska**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Ben Sasse, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Ben Sasse was re-elected.\n\n20. **Nevada**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (open seat due to retirement of Senator Dean Heller)\n    - **Result:** Catherine Cortez Masto (Democrat) won the seat.\n\n21. **New Hampshire**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Jeanne Shaheen, Democrat)\n    - **Result:** Jeanne Shaheen was re-elected.\n\n22. **North Carolina**\n    - **Seat:** Class III (incumbent Thom Tillis, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Thom Tillis was re-elected.\n\n23. **North Dakota**\n    - **Seat:** Class III (incumbent John Hoeven, Republican)\n    - **Result:** John Hoeven was re-elected.\n\n24. **Ohio**\n    - **Seat:** Class III (incumbent Rob Portman, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Rob Portman was re-elected.\n\n25. **Oklahoma**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Jim Inhofe, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Jim Inhofe was re-elected.\n\n26. **Oregon**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Ron Wyden, Democrat)\n    - **Result:** Ron Wyden was re-elected.\n\n27. **Pennsylvania**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Pat Toomey, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Pat Toomey was re-elected.\n\n28. **South Carolina**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Lindsey Graham, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Lindsey Graham was re-elected.\n\n29. **South Dakota**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (incumbent Mike Rounds, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Mike Rounds was re-elected.\n\n30. **Tennessee**\n    - **Seat:** Class II (open seat due to retirement of Senator Lamar Alexander)\n    - **Result:** Marsha Blackburn (Republican) won the seat.\n\n31. **Texas**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Ted Cruz, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Ted Cruz was re-elected.\n\n32. **Utah**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Mike Lee, Republican)\n    - **Result:** Mike Lee was re-elected.\n\n33. **Vermont**\n    - **Seat:** Class I (incumbent Bernie Sanders, Independent)\n    - **Result:** Bernie Sanders was re-elected.\n\n### **Special Elections:**\n\n1. **Mississippi**\n   - **Seat:** Class II (open seat due to the death of Senator Thad Cochran)\n   - **Result:** Cindy Hyde-Smith (Republican) was appointed and subsequently won the special election.\n\n2. **North Dakota**\n   - **Seat:** Class III (special election to fill the vacancy left by the death of Senator John Hoeven's spouse)\n   - **Result:** Kevin Cramer (Republican) won the special election.\n\n### **Key Takeaways:**\n\n- **Party Control:** Before the 2018 elections, the U.S. Senate was closely divided. The Republicans gained additional seats, increasing their majority.\n- **Notable Races:** \n  - **Missouri:** Incumbent Roy Blunt (R) was defeated by Josh Hawley (R), signaling a shift within the Republican Party.\n  - **Georgia:** The high-profile race between David Perdue (R) and Jon Ossoff (D) gained national attention, with Perdue ultimately securing the seat.\n  - **Alaska:** The seat changed from Democratic to Republican control with Dan Sullivan defeating incumbent Mark Begich.\n\nThe 2018 Senate elections played a significant role in shaping the legislative landscape leading into the 116th United States Congress.",
